<div class="prepend-1 span-12 append-1 last calendar" id="calendar">
	<div id="id22b1" class="span-3 sidebar">
		<h3>1 &ndash; 8</h3>
		<div>
			<div id="item-327" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22b2"><p><em>The Times</em>, no great friend to fundamentalists in the U.S., clucks at the <a href='http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/30/world/europe/30turkey.html'>&#8220;fear&#8221; of religious &#8220;lifestyle&#8221;</a> in the Turkish thinking class. &#8220;Prejudices among secular Turks have their roots in Turkey’s education system.&#8221; Yeah. It&#8217;s called science. We have it here too, except sometimes in <a href='http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F70F12F93B5B0C708CDDA10894DE404482&amp;showabstract=1'>Kansas</a>. When there are &#8220;questions like whether to separate the sexes in public swimming pools,&#8221; it&#8217;s not a subscription to <em>Maizah Stewart Living</em> they&#8217;re worried about.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 1</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-327">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-328" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22b3"><p>Foreign tourists are <a href='http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/2/story.cfm?c_id=2&amp;objectid=10436518'>afraid to visit us</a>: &#8220;In a recent poll of international travellers&#8230; 70 percent of respondents said they feared U.S. officials more than terrorists or criminals.&#8221; Those clever foreigners, correctly estimating <a href='http://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2006/11/perceived_risk_1.html'>risks</a> and stuff. [via <em>b.b.</em>]</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 1</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-328">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-330" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22b4"><p><em>Wonkette</em> has some <a href='http://wonkette.com/politics/dept&apos;-of-hilarious-blog-comments/hey-mexicans-leave-your-dope-at-home-in-mexico-256803.php'>fun with barely literate comments</a>: &#8220;white Americans are having a crucial debate about the tragic crisis in the comments of this <em>New York Times</em> blog we just found.&#8221;</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 1</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-330">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-331" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22b5"><p>Love <a href='http://www.theonion.com/content/magazine/the_10_products_that_will_make'>this</a>.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 1</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-331">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-334" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22b6"><p>SFGate is able to have an <a href='http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/sfgate/detail?blogid=14&amp;entry_id=16036'>honest opinion on carbon tax</a>: &#8220;The most inconvenient truth in Washington is that nothing is more important than keeping energy as cheap as Hugo Chavez, Mahmoud Ahmadinejad and King Abdullah will allow.&#8221; Predictably, their first commenter starts screeching about the poor, says they are &#8220;going to starve&#8221; without their cheap gas. Funny, I&#8217;m feeling sated and haven&#8217;t been in a car since February.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 2</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-334">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-335" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22b7"><p>Presumed brain dead mega-brand shockingly has an <a href='http://www.subtraction.com/archives/2007/0501_to_wrap_it_u.php'>efficiency and quality enhancing idea</a>: &#8220;there is a subtle, dotted grid pattern printed on the backside of Hallmark gift wrap that serves as a guide as customers cut away the necessary amount to wrap presents.&#8221;</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 2</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-335">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-339" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22b8"><p>Editorial integrity: at least <a href='http://gawker.com/news/core-principles/steve-jobs-may-be-hazardous-to-your-job-257411.php'>some people are still trying</a>.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 3</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-339">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-341" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22b9"><p>This BlackBerry marketing copy, <a href='http://daringfireball.net/linked/2007/may#thu-03-bbcurve'>spotted</a> by <em>Daring Fireball</em>, is delicious: &#8220;Check the latest fashion, or even automotive trends online. Then send links to friends so they can see what&#8217;s hot&#8230; and what&#8217;s not.&#8221; Love the kicker; you go conference room B-3!</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 3</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-341">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-342" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22ba"><p>The most annoying thing about the 2002 lead up to our glorious invasion of Iraq was the Dem&#8217;s claim that their blank check for <em class='smcp'>war</em> was to be used only as a threat. Ha ha&#8212;that <em>threatening</em> act removed them entirely from the decision to go from sabre-rattling to sabre-stabbing. So the decider then decided to stab (who could have seen <em>that</em> coming?), and it was like one of those kung-fu movies where the stabbed guy looks up, grins, and proceeds to kick your ass. Anyway, Clinton wants to <a href='http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/04/washington/04cong.html'>stop payment on that blank check</a>.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 4</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-342">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-346" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22bb"><p>Gould gets <a href='http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/04/opinion/04gould.html'>op-ed space in <em>The Times</em></a> to carry out revenge for the televised beat-down she suffered a few weeks back. The paper must realize that the <em class='smcp'>blogs</em> are their allies in the war against successful dumb people on television.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 7</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-346">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-347" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22bc"><p>From <a href='http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/04/opinion/04gould.html'>E.G.&#8217;s satisfying op-ed</a> (yes, of last week, but we were in Cheecaaow, where they do not have <em>The Times</em> or <em>Gawker</em>): &#8220;Is there anyone who reads the Page Six column in The New York Post or Star magazine credulous enough to believe that starlets are really &#8216;spotted&#8217; enjoying, say, a specific brand of vodka?&#8221;</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 7</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-347">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-348" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22bd"><p><em>Slate</em> chimes in on a hobby horse of ours, the <a href='http://www.slate.com/id/2165581/'>horror of wedding consumerism</a>: &#8220;Today&#8217;s marriage ceremony is indeed a statement of love: the love of buying things, and, more particularly, buying things that have been personalized to express one&#8217;s taste and, so the industry tells us, the essence of who one is.&#8221; (We did manage to <a href='http://technically.us/doc/articles/2006/11/05/weddings-worst-and-only-use-of-the-word-“joyous”'>say it worse</a> ourselves.) Along those <em>essential</em> lines, a downtown mall in Chicago (it was cold!) is plastered with the tagline, &#8220;Defining You.&#8221;</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 7</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-348">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-351" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22be"><p><a href='http://www.slate.com/id/2165669/'><em>Ad Report Card</em></a>: &#8220;BP hopes to cement itself as the most &#8216;green&#8217; of the massive oil companies. To this end &#8230; [stations] hand out trading cards with environmentally sensitive tips for kids &#8221; Here&#8217;s a tip: don&#8217;t produce useless throw-away cards.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 8</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-351">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-352" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22bf"><p>Until now, we saw Keith McNally as a smart businessman with a knack for selling a Disneyfied version of smoke-clogged French <em>brasseries</em> to people who should know better. (Have Balthazar fans ever eaten in one of those, even? Our unbidden Proustian memories springing from red <em>banquettes</em> are decidedly <em>malheureux</em>.) Now we see that he&#8217;s <a href='http://gawker.com/news/sour-grapes-and-convenient-femiladyism/frank-bruni-hates-ladies-claims-crazy-mcnally-258702.php'>just another pathetic restaurateur</a> who thinks popular = better-than-good reviews. Others would kill for that &#8220;token&#8221; one star, Mr. McDisney.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 8</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-352">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div>
	</div><div id="id22c0" class="span-3 sidebar">
		<h3>9 &ndash; 16</h3>
		<div>
			<div id="item-353" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22c1"><p>More of McNally <a href='http://nyobserver.com/print/53942/full'>being a prick</a>: &#8220;The smaller-minded critics, however (and this includes Bruni), don&#8217;t care for my places, because when they&#8217;re there, they feel disempowered. They don&#8217;t have the power, as they so often do, to alter the fate of the place. It drives them to distraction. But it only makes me smile.&#8221; Well, that settles it: EuroRestauDisneys are the new &#8220;Irish pubs.&#8221; Avoid.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 9</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-353">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-354" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22c2"><p>Wimpy frontiersmen who&#8217;ve chosen to settle in the savage desert now demand that <a href='http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/wired27b/~3/115383818/congressman_wan.html'>wolves be introduced in Central Park</a> if they are to be let loose in their big desert back yards. Just wait until we reanimate T. rex, New Mexico, then you will see how much fun the wild wild west can be!</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 9</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-354">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-356" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22c3"><p><em>Times</em> distills radical Islam to, simply, &#8220;religion,&#8221; in <a href='http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/10/nyregion/10plot.html'>Religion Guided 3 Held in Fort Dix Plot</a>: &#8220;if you get too much to the religion, you get out of your mind and you do stupid things,&#8221; says distant relative. No doubt&#8212;this was the <a href='http://wonkette.com/politics/lost-the-plot-dept%27/feds-nix-dix-six-258602.php'>stupidest plot ever</a>.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 10</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-356">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-357" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22c4"><p>What, an <a href='http://blog.wired.com/business/2007/05/pc_world_brings.html'>Editor in Chief beat a Chief Executive Officer</a> in an editorial deathmatch? That great, but the fallout will further elevate managerial titles in all our offices. <em>Good morning, Mr. Jesus God Chieftain Executional Admiral Officer!</em></p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 10</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-357">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-358" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22c5"><p>A <em>Times</em> opinion piece frets over the <a href='http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/10/business/10scene.html'>canard of poor <abbr>NYC</abbr> drivers</a>: &#8220;Although most people who currently commute by car into Manhattan are not poor, some are, and for these drivers, paying $8 each day would be difficult.&#8221; (As <em>TNYer</em> <a href='http://www.newyorker.com/talk/comment/2007/05/07/070507taco_talk_kolbert'>bravely pointed out</a>, &#8220;that is precisely the point.&#8221;) The piece goes on to propose a system of vouchers for the poor (except there it adopts the vague &#8220;worker&#8221;), that could be used when they &#8220;have no choice but to drive,&#8221; and resold otherwise. Sure, great way to progress against the bourgeoisie and stuff! We non-driving bougies will get on board just as soon as we see some evidence of these <em>indentured driving poor</em>.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 10</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-358">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-378" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22c6"><p>We weren&#8217;t kidding <a href='http://technically.us/city/x/my-view-from-west-ambler-johnston-hall'>about gun-crazy Virgina</a>. (Yes, that <abbr>VT</abbr> post will be fronted until Jesus comes again.) Now they&#8217;ve written laws to <a href='http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/09/AR2007050902573.html'>prevent <abbr>NYC</abbr> from busting their gun shops</a> for selling mountains of guns illegally (they do have <em>some</em> gun laws to be broken) that get used in bad places like here and never in God&#8217;s blessed Virginia except by foreign loners. <abbr>NYC</abbr> responds with the obvious: &#8220;We wish [Virginia] was as aggressive in enforcing the laws that prevent illegal guns from getting in the hands of criminals&#8221; blah blah &#8220;gun lobby.&#8221; (It&#8217;s not the lobby driving things there; the state <em>is for gun lovers</em>, but whatever works!) [via <em>Wonkette</em>]</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 10</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-378">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-379" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22c7"><p>Schneier writes about <a href='http://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2007/05/is_big_brother.html'>how today isn&#8217;t like 1984</a>. It isn&#8217;t because Lady Macintosh threw a hammer. Or, it is, in the sense that all computer use creates a surveillance society inadvertently.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 11</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-379">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-382" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22c8"><p>Funny but impossible to believe <a href='http://newyork.craigslist.org/mnh/roo/328207798.html'>craigslist posting</a> found <a href='http://gawker.com/news/live-with-a-sadult/get-nervous-get-nervous-259687.php'>by <em>Gawker</em></a>: &#8220;I have a box set of ally McBeal and Full House (I&#8217;m from San Francisco) and like watch them often.&#8221; And we&#8217;re from New York and we&#8217;re addicted to <em>Friends</em>. We did <em>not</em> stop watching after the first season when whatever happened to Ross and what&#8217;s-her-hair! (We were 14 or something and not from New York; don&#8217;t judge us for watching even that much.)</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 11</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-382">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-406" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22c9"><p>One or two new <abbr>NYPD</abbr> officers are so poor, they <a href='http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/12/nyregion/12recruits.html'>have to take the degrading subway to work</a>. Striking lead photo depicts never before seen image of uniformed officer waiting on platform.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 12</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-406">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-424" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22ca"><p>Evil <a href='http://www.ashersarlin.com/archives/2007/05/happy_mothers_d.php'>mother&#8217;s day cards</a>. <em>Card B</em> works fine actually if mom&#8217;s birthday was on Sunday, which it was.</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 14</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-424">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
			<div id="item-425" class="entry">
				<div class="note-edit-line"></div>
				<div id="id22cb"><p>Men and women are <a href='http://itre.cis.upenn.edu/~myl/languagelog/archives/004491.html'><em class='smcp'>hardwired</em> to talk totally different</a>&#8212;but only if you believe those absurd press-grubbing gender studies that come out every four and a half months. Nobody please tell <em>Slate</em>!</p></div>
				<div class="byline">
					<span>
							<span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>
							<span>May 14</span>
							<a href="../../../city/archive/2007/5/#item-425">#</a>
					</span>
				</div>
</div>
			
		</div><div>
